alumni of the K-12 Milton Hershey School. He arrives just as a scandal erupts that raises questions about the outsized power of the private trust over public life. Kurie draws on diverse voices across the community to show how philanthropy stirs passions and interests well beyond intended beneficiaries. In Chocolate We Trust reveals the cultural significance of Hershey as a forerunner to socially conscious corporations and the cult of the entrepreneur-philanthropist. The Hershey story encapsulates the dreams and wishes of today's consumer-citizens: the dream of becoming personally successful, and the wish that the most affluent among us will serve the common good.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCompany townszPennsylvaniazHershey. 0aTrusts and trusteeszPennsylvaniazHershey. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aBusiness.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.  aPublic Policy.  aReligious Studies.  aUrban Studies.40uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229473640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812294736423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812294736.jpg  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK